For SRS based beam forming, are the 200 or more users using the same time-frequency resources?
For SRS based beam forming, are the 200 or more users using the same time-frequency resources?

The MU-MIMO features are needed on top of the SRS algorithm to share the time-frequency resources, but only for limited amount of simultaneous users. This is a great capacity benefit to the network.(Venugopal V N (Nokia) asked "For SRS based beam forming, are the 200 or more users using the same time-frequency resources?")

The feature supports frequency domain multiplexing scheduling between sub-band beamforming users and legacy beamforming users (SU-MIMO and/or MU-MIMO) per slot basis.(Venugopal V N (Nokia) asked "For SRS based beam forming, are the 200 or more users using the same time-frequency resources?")
does the sub band SRS feature apply to ALL 5G mMIMO radio families?
does the sub band SRS feature apply to ALL 5G mMIMO radio families?
Yes, FR1-TDD(does the sub band SRS feature apply to ALL 5G mMIMO radio families?)

5gC000524 - does any operator have it enabled? What is the recommendation to use it?
5gC000524 - does any operator have it enabled? What is the recommendation to use it?

There was a bullet in the slide #33 stating that in practice the feature has been replaced by CB008305 including enhanced functionality for the same. 5GC000524 is a pre-requisite feature for CB008305.(5gC000524 - does any operator have it enabled? What is the recommendation to use it?)
16 DL MU-MIMO must be very good for FWA where the CPEs are at fixed locations and can give good separation
16 DL MU-MIMO must be very good for FWA where the CPEs are at fixed locations and can give good separation

Exactly! Stationary subscribers scattered throughout the cell is a perfect use case for the feature providing performance boost for high data users.(Tor Aarland (Nokia) asked "16 DL MU-MIMO must be very good for FWA where the CPEs are at fixed locations and can give good separation")
We should clearly mention that MU-MIMO gains (only) apply when there is high-load in a cell (40-70% of PRB usage), otherwise 'just' latency is reduced a bit ...

We should clearly mention that MU-MIMO gains (only) apply when there is high-load in a cell (40-70% of PRB usage), otherwise 'just' latency is reduced a bit ...

Good point Arno.MU-MIMO features require higher load in order to perform optimally as they require sufficient amount of potential pairing devices.(Arno Koch (Nokia) asked "We should clearly mention that MU-MIMO gains (only) apply when there is high-load in a cell (40-70% of PRB usage), otherwise 'just' latency is reduced a bit ...
